This case is being appealed. If the court makes a decision in a case that a party disagrees with, the party may have the right to seek review by a higher court to determine if the trial court's decision was correct. Appeals are most often made after a trial or final decision in a case, but an appeal can also occur before a final decision.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:53 p.m. - Response/record by Atty. De Peters. Response by the Court.
2:55 p.m. - Record by the Court who based upon record/review grants the defendant's motion for new trial. Discussion as to next steps.
Court reinstates the bond of January 30, 2015.  Discussion as to whether defendant will be transferred to Walworth County. Discussion.
2:57 p.m. - Discussion off the record between the parties. 
3:00 p.m. - Record by De Peters who asks that matter be set out for 30 days to allow time for State to decide if they will appeal the decision. If matter is going to go to trial again, a new attorney will need to be appointed for Mr. Medina.

Defendant Lupe Medina in court by Zoom from Oshkosh Correctional with attorney Marcella De Peters by Zoom.  Zeke Wiedenfeld appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Zoom. Court in session @ 1:02 p.m. Appearances made. Matter before the Court for Machner hearing. Record by the Court as to all appearances by Zoom. Atty. De Peters confirms that her client does not object to Zoom appearances. 
1:02 p.m. - Defense calls Kaitlin Friberg who is duly sworn by the Court and responds to direct examination of Atty. De Peters. Exhibit #1 will be marked once sent to Clerk and Court receives with no objections.
1:15 p.m. - Cross examination by DA Wiedenfeld. Objection by Atty. De Peters as to line of questioning. Response by Atty. Wiedenfeld. Response by the Court who sustains the objection. Atty. Wiedenfeld reserves the right to recall witness after further testimony. Court will address when the time come. Cross examination continues.
1:48 p.m. - Redirect by Atty. De Peters.
1:52 p.m. - Discussion as to how to contact witness if State wants to recall.
1:52 p.m. - DE calls Travis Schwantes who is duly sworn by the Court and responds to direct examination of Atty. De Peters.
2:14 p.m. - Cross examination by DA Wiedenfeld. Objection as to line of questioning. Response by Atty. Wiedenfeld. Court overules the objection.
2:18 p.m. - Atty. De Peters addresses Mr. Medina as to waiver of privilege based upon questions of the State. Response by Mr. Medina that he has no objection to waiving privilege. 
2:21 p.m. - State resumes questioning of Atty. Schwantes
2:44 p.m. - Redirect by Atty. De Peters
2:47 p.m. - Recross by DA Wiedenfeld
2:51 p.m. - Redirect by Atty. De Peters
2:53 p.m. - Discussion as to further witnesses. Court in recess for break. 
3:12 p.m. - Court back in session with same appearances. State calls Investigator Kirsten Stilke who is duly sworn by the Court and responds to direct examination of Atty. Wiedenfeld.
3:23 p.m. - Cross examination by Atty. De Peters.
3:28 p.m. - Witness excused. State calls Detective Kimberly Bass who is duly sworn by the Court and responds to direct examination of Atty. Wiedenfeld. 
3:33 p.m. - Objection by Atty. DePere - hearsay. Atty. Wiedenfeld will recall Ms. Frieberg. Court goes off the record to allow Atty. DePere to call her to reappear for questioning by Atty. Wiedenfeld. 
3:37 p.m. - Back on the record. Court makes a statement regarding discussion off the record. Court addressees hearsay objection made by Atty. DePere. Response by Atty. Wiedenfeld. 
3:38 p.m. - Record by Atty. De Peters as to credibility of witness that should be determined by jury and is not proper for this hearing. Further record as to relevance.
3:41 p.m. - Response by the Court who addresses Atty. Wiedenfeld as to arugment by Atty. De Peters regarding credibility and relevance. 
3:43 p.m. - Court finds testimony relevant but questions credibility argument made by the State.
3:44 p.m. - Court addresses Atty. De Peters as to cases cited in her brief.
3:49 p.m. - Court goes off the record to allow attorneys and the Court to reveiw the cases cited as to credibility issues.
4:36 p.m. - Court back in session with same appearances. Court makes a statement as to material he reviewed. Response by Atty. De Peters. Response by the Court. Response by Atty. Wiedenfeld. Response by the Court who reads from case to the record regarding concurrent opinion and guidance of Justice Crooks. Court adopts the guidance reflected in Justice Crooks' decision but also admits it is a high standard.
4:40 p.m. - Court recalls Kaitlin Friberg who is reminded she is still under oath. Witness responds to questions by ADA Wiedenfeld.
4:48 p.m. - Cross examination by Atty. De Peters
4:53 p.m. - Witness is excused by the Court. 
4:54 p.m. - Record by the Court who does not find that testimony of Ms. Friberg does not rise to the standard set forth by Justice Crooks. Court goes off the record to address briefing schedule - oral decision. Response brief by the State due on April 16th, Reply brief due on 4/30.  Court sets oral decision. Attorneys to appear in person. Defendant to appear via Zoom. Court in recess.
